### Behavior proof points in the decoded payload

The storage runner now has an end-to-end static path into the dispatcher:

```text
0x10052841 entry path
  -> 0x10052a81 searches candidate storage files
  -> 0x10051b39 builds the runtime context from the recovered storage object
  -> 0x1005079d parses the storage object into internal containers
  -> 0x10051f85 registers top-level handler groups
  -> 0x10051c15 iterates parsed top-level entries
  -> 0x10051d99 dispatches each entry directly or through CreateThread
  -> 0x10051d49 calls 0x10051e51
  -> 0x1000c6e5 resolves the entry group and calls 0x1000cc05
```

`0x10051f85` registers the same top-level group IDs routed by the master dispatcher: `300`, `400`, `500`, `600`, `700`, `1000`, `0x44c`, `0x4b0`, `0x514`, `0x5dc`, `0x6a4`, `0x708`, `0x76c`, `0x7d0`, `0x834`, and `0x898`. This makes the dispatcher table part of the parsed-storage execution model rather than a detached helper table.

The key bridge is `0x1000c6e5`. It looks up a group object using the parsed entry's group value, stores a next/continuation value from `entry+0x28`, and then calls:

```text
0x1000cc05(context, resolved_group_object, entry+0x10, entry+0x18, entry+0x20)
```

After the dispatcher returns, `0x10051e51` either invokes the returned object through `0x10007c19` or, when the parsed entry has a non-null `entry+0x20` and `entry+0x10` is not `0x5e1` or `0x5e2`, through `0x10007b21`. It then uses `0x1000c9cd` to find the next entry whose first qword matches the stored continuation value. If no match is found, `0x1000c9cd` returns `0xffffffffffffffff` and the loop stops.

The decoded shellcode is command-driven. The top-level dispatcher at `0x1000cc05` reads the value stored at `object+8` through `0x10006159`, then routes that value to grouped handlers. Static routing observed so far:

